There are two key differences causing the values to diverge:

Difference 1: Profile Training Data Split
Notebook (line profile = build_reference_profile(train_df ...)):

Builds profile from train_df = 157 rows (all original rows, explicitly excluding the 7 injected case rows)
This is clean historical data only
Lambda (dynamic_drift_profile.py -> prepare_drift_data):

Calls prepare_drift_data(df) which splits as: historical_df = df.iloc[:-1] and latest_df = df.iloc[-1:]
Builds profile from historical_df = all rows except the very last one
If the data file contains the injected rows, the profile would include the first 6 injected case rows (CASE_1 through CASE_6) in the training data -- only CASE_7 would be the "latest" row being scored
This is the biggest source of divergence. The notebook carefully excludes all injected rows from training; the Lambda naively takes "everything except last row" as training data. So:

The Lambda's mean, std, p99 are polluted by the extreme values of CASE_1-CASE_6
The notebook's mean, std, p99 are computed from clean historical data only
For example, CASE_1 (CASE_1_SPEND_SHOCK_3X) has 3x spend values. If those 3x values are included in the Lambda's training data, they inflate the mean and std, which changes the z-score for the row being tested.

Difference 2: Which Row Gets Scored
Notebook: Scores each injected case row individually against the clean profile (loops over all 7 cases)

Lambda: Only scores the last row (retailer_df.iloc[-1]). If the data has all 7 injected rows appended, the Lambda scores only CASE_7 (the last one), not CASE_1.

Difference 3: KPI Residual Calculation
Notebook score_one_week(): Computes y_hat directly from the ridge beta and the current row's features. The resid_z uses resid_mean and resid_std from the profile.

Lambda detect_kpi_behavior_break(): Also uses _predict_log_kpi_from_profile() to get y_hat, BUT it additionally computes kpi_delta and spend_delta between retailer_df.iloc[-1] and retailer_df.iloc[-2], and checks for opposite_direction. The notebook's score_one_week doesn't have this opposite-direction logic.

Summary
Aspect	Notebook	Lambda
Training data	157 clean rows (excludes injected)	All rows except last (includes other injected rows)
Row scored	Each case individually	Only the last row in file
Profile stats	Pure historical baseline	Contaminated by injected outliers
KPI check	Pure residual z-score	Residual z + opposite direction + event suppression
The contaminated training data is the main reason the z-scores and p99 values differ. To get matching values, the Lambda's prepare_drift_data() would need to filter out rows tagged as injected cases, or the test data fed to the Lambda should only contain clean historical rows + one test case at a time.
